[{"sha":"ed84f7611a9629657dbf5073c8b50a42e48337a7","author":{"email":"5bcb0c34b484f21048fb46d802116fb172e4e0a2@google.com","name":"Frederik Gossen"},"message":"[ShapeAnalysis] Eliminate more redundant shape constraints in real-world cases

Eliminate more redundant `cstr_reshapable` constraints. Collect all the factors
before comparing the number of elements and the dynamic shape for compatibility.
Previously, we did this only for the symbolic expression that falls out of the
`num_elements` op, not for the individual dimensions of the dynamic shape. With
this, we are able to eliminate the `cstr_reshapable` in the real-world
integration test.

[{"sha":"2f8a3286f3e60a29c58bd5136c389481705884b7","author":{"email":"117600c937fb2af1218bd1d47c746d36a58fc7b4@google.com","name":"Eugene Zhulenev"},"message":"[tf:tfrt] Add benchmarks runner using the TF -> TFRT -> BEF fallback lowering path

This allows to easily compare compilation vs interpretation performance. Compilation benchmark doesn't include fixed overheads that are present at runtime (~200-300ns), so it only makes sense to compare numbers when the input size is relatively large.

Example: Fresh1 benchmark (~2x-3x speedup)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Benchmark                                Time             CPU   Iterations
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
BM_cpurt_Fresh1/0/process_time      570480 ns       569666 ns         1250
BM_cpurt_Fresh1/4/process_time      254597 ns      1018092 ns          668
BM_cpurt_Fresh1/16/process_time     154314 ns      1827423 ns          377
BM_cpurt_Fresh1/32/process_time     166876 ns      2936675 ns          235
BM_tfrt_Fresh1/0/process_time      1820103 ns      1823890 ns          367
BM_tfrt_Fresh1/4/process_time       618316 ns      2259034 ns          304
BM_tfrt_Fresh1/16/process_time      461534 ns      5754382 ns          118
BM_tfrt_Fresh1/32/process_time      403252 ns      6492160 ns          107
